defaultLetter submitted by DefradefaultPlastic bag charge carbon emissions analysis defaultT
defaulthe Committee has asked if we c
defaultould
default provide further information about the carbon emissions analysis
default which we provided in our written evidence
default. 
defaultThe Government has
default not 
defaultbeen using a 
defaultcarbon reduction argument as the main basis for the policy
default to reduce the distribution of single-use plastic carrier bags
default and increase the number of bags being reused by consumers. 
defaultThe main benefits of this policy are in terms of a reduction in litter on land and at sea.
default I
defaultn addition this
default will also reduce the environmental
default,
default resource 
defaultand economic 
defaultcost of their production
default, storage and transport
default.
default Until this point in the process, therefore, we had not carried out a thorough review of the relevant carbon data. When we did so an error came to light in an estimate of the benefits carried out in 2012; this over-estimated the carbon impact significantly due to how the original 2006 Environment Agency figures were being used.
defaultThe analysis set out below therefore differs 
defaultfrom that in our original evidence and we would like to take this opportunity to rectify the error.
defaultT
defaulthe 2006 Environment Agency’s assessment of the life cycle environmental impacts of different carrier bags presents CO
default2
defaulte figures for each type of bag (single-use plastic bag, paper bag, bag for life, etc) based on a comparable ‘functional unit’, i.e. carrying one month’s shopping (483 items) home. For example 82 single-use bags are required to fulfil this function, with associated emissions of 1.57 kg CO
default2
defaulte, while 61 bags for life fulfil the same function with emissions of 1.39 kg CO
default2
defaulte (if each bag for life is re-used 5 times). 
defaultThe error was to 
defaultuse the CO
default2
defaulte figures associated with one month’s shopping as referring to individual bags (i.e. one single-use plastic bag was assigned emissions of 1.57kg CO
default2
defaulte), thus overstating the carbon impact of the charge by a factor of 82.
defaultThe estimates are calculated on an embedded emissions approach. 
defaultThis means that much of the emissions reduction occur outside of the UK
default as most plastic bags are manufactured abroad
default. 
defaultI have attached a revised copy of the Defra 
defaultwritten evidence
default 
defaultand 
defaulthave 
defaultset out the areas requiring amendment below. If possible 
defaultwe 
defaultwould also like to 
defaultcorrect 
defaultone of the statements 
defaultgiven by 
defaultthe Minister, 
defaultDan 
defaultRogerson
default, during his 
defaultoral evidence. 
defaultAmendmentsdefault (in bold)default: defaultEAC written evidence default“
defaultParagraph 19. The charge in England is also expected to reduce the local environmental and biodiversity impact of littered bags. The indicative reduction in single-use plastic bag usage outlined would cause an associated fall in GHG emissions of around 
default97,000-130,000default tonnes
default CO
default2
default equivalent (not taking into account impacts of plastic bags for life or bin liners).
default”
default“
